Lebanon's All-Out Crisis
Beyrouth — — Reminiscently, a typical financial crisis usually has premonitions before it occurs; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon's situation now is the same; a predictable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economy and political system have been supported by external loans, which inevitably led to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, external capital inflows had to stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This sudden stop of capital has brought a triple crisis to this country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
The current account deficit of Lebanon is as high as 25% of its GDP, and its export base is too small to even pay for the necessary import costs.
The second issue is the fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals over 150% of its GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the weight of economic recession, with a large budget deficit, already reaching 10% of GDP in 2019, and still expanding rapidly.
The most important thing is that Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
The main banks, which received the majority of foreign capital inflows, invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolio), and are now virtually insolvent.
These crises are driving Lebanon's economy into the abyss.
Companies that are eager to take loans and imports have already begun laying off employees or closing down completely.
Economic downturn may lead to a Great Depression in Lebanon.
The primary capital source supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but diaspora, who are attracted by high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate pegged to the US dollar, and invest accordingly.
So, it's no surprise that there are signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect, and lowering the national savings rate to an unlikely level of 3% of GDP.
The degree of inequality is very high, and it's still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by around 50%, significantly weakening the tradable sectors.
Due to a lack of export commodities and services, Lebanon has been losing educated young people.
However, more importantly, large-scale capital inflow allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their position through patronage rather than merit.
These elites have squeezed wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated sectarian ruling elite.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic area, it failed to meet basic needs.
Not even electricity supply was continuous and reliable, and the macroeconomic challenges facing the country were completely left unaddressed.
Financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the country's ruling power has been overwhelmingly biased in favor of the elite class in its response to Lebanon's economic problems, indicating that the crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, and further solidifying sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including politicians in power, to decide how to extract cash in quantities.
In fact, this allows the elite to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to obtain deposits.
Meanwhile, the central bank has lowered the interest rate on deposits, but not yet lowered the interest rate on public debt, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon has continued to repay its main foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling state assets to elite-related entities at throwaway prices.
At the same time, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while allowing the elite to obtain low-dollar exchange rates, ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly falling free market exchange rate. The current free market exchange rate has dropped by 40%.
When the country starts printing lira to pay civil servant salaries, depreciation will accelerate.
Actually, the central bank has already been using the lira to pay interest on US dollar deposits (over 80% of all deposits are in US dollars) and thereby has created conditions for eliminating public debt through inflation.
As the 'liraization' of debt through shareholder holdings pushes the cost of reducing debt onto depositors, bank capital is basically exempt.
If this situation becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class would greatly decrease due to the reduction in actual wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The process of educated young people's migration will accelerate, and even the economic benefits of the migrant community - which this system relies on - will be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system, and this population system can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
The end result will be that Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to that of Venezuela.
Compared to this, the establishment of the new republic driven by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and its performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more sustainable in the environment, position the country as a cultural hub, and create more synergy with the immigrant community.
To achieve these objectives, the reform movement hopes to seek orderly reduction of public debt, which would be guaranteed by bank capital and enforced reduction of deposits of 1% of account holders who hold more than 50% of total deposits.
They support moderate currency devaluation and thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices, and increased spending on social projects and infrastructure.
Under the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of the next Lebanese government is part of a larger struggle in the process of seeking a new political solution for the country.
Financial crisis posed a mortal threat to this country; but it also represented an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon hangs in the balance.
